  comment          = {`` identifies how, both in theory and practice, climate scientists can engage in policy advocacy in a way that is acceptable to them and their scientific community''

a new way of defining advocacy (it is different from support, opinion and manipulation) - it is a persuasive plea or `` plea in active support of something in order that others may be persuaded to act''

advocacy can be informative or prescriptive [this relates to the discussion in my thesis about advocacy]

advocacy contextual factors:
- voice - the person advocating
- content - what they are advocating 
- audience - who is being advocated to and how they experience the advocacy

roles that scientists can engage in when communicating fall within the advocacy spectrum [this relates to my roles summary in my thesis]:
- non-engagement with policy - like Pielke's pure scientist
- policy advice - Pielke's science arbiter and honest broker 
- action advocacy (unclear boundary between this and specific policy advocacy) - something must be done, somewhere between being policy descriptive and policy prescriptive
- specific policy advocacy - what type of action should be taken
- does not include unacceptable advocacy - Pielke's stealth advocate

different audences may hear the same communication as coming from a different place in this spectrum (section 5.2)

Interview 47 climate scientists to explore concerns about advocacy and the practical methods they use to manage tensions

Identify a range of tensions that scientists experience such as
- scientists claiming that they were not advocating but the research finds that there were underlying values and judgements meant that their communication is advocacy
- scientists using the audience's reactions and actions as a measure of how well they comprehended the scientific communication [but actions may be due to some other factor not information deficit]

Discuss acceptible advocacy and compare to bias advocacy or abuse of position
Long discussion of values

establish eight methods scientists can use that allow scientists to engage in policy advocacy whilst also preserving their scientific credibility and independence:
1. speak out as a group
2. be aware how you are seen
3. frame communications well
4. engage in dialogue
5. state your values
6. be clear about where your expertise stops
7. do your homework
8. get the communication skills you need

discussed in \url{https://www.yourbrainonclimate.com/1817605/episodes/16020011-the-neutrality-myth-with-lydia-messling}},
