  comment          = {Brilliant paper

Where ``technologies of hubris'' (p238) are the means with which we like to think we create accountability, e.g. controlling risk by predicting (safety, efficacy, economic efficiency p226) using (risk assessment, cost benefit analysis, climate modelling p238) we need more ``technologies of humility'' that are institutionalised habits of thought that come to grips with the unknown, the uncertain, the ambiguous and the uncontrollable p227. This requires more than formal participation but an ``an intellectual environment in which citizens bring their knowledge and skills to bear on the resolution of common problems'' p227

``The issue, in other words, is no longer whether the public should have a say in technical decisions, but how to promote more meaningful interaction among policy-makers, scientific experts, corporate producers, and the public'' p238

Science is no longer a ``pipeline'' but more dispersed, context-dependent, problem oriented (Mode 2) p226

