  year             = {2023},
  comment          = {Considers the science, economics and diplomancy

Faster progress with the same level of political will and social will and resources

The science:

Is essential - we need this to know about climate change

However research that is done and communicated is in the form of forecasting - Sharpe argues for more risk assessment

forecasting is - what will happen and do we care?
risk assessment is - what is the worst that could happen to what we care about and then how likely is that? e.g. what are our limits to tolerance

Science culture of risk is very averse to false positives unlike insurance or defence who are very averse to false negatives

Suggest risk assessment exercises in each country brining together risk experts and climate scientists. 

The economics:

There are irreducable uncertainties and inherent subjectivity (e.g. about what we care about) and so economists cannot reasonably put numbers on the economics of the problem
They can put numbers on the economics of the solution

Economics assumes equilibrium which is fundamentally flawed, particularly in a rapidly changing world - constant change, uncertainty, complex dynamics

If you think of system in equilibrium, you tax existing systems. If you assume it is dynamic, you invest in new approaches. Analogy is move from horse to car - we didn't do it by putting a tax on horse manure

The diplomacy:

diplomacy has a number of approaches that could be used:
- scale - don't negotiate everything all at once, break down the sectors and negotiate these separately
- participation - don't try to get everyone in the room, bring in enough to influence the rest
- timing - don't create targets well into the future when governments are very uncertain [and largely don't care] but work on near term objectives and changes may be greater than anticipated},
