  title            = {Framing mechanisms: the interpretive policy entrepreneur's toolbox},
  year             = {2018},
  number           = {4},
  pages            = {406--427},
  volume           = {12},
  comment          = {Present the ``interpretative policy entrepreneur'' [IPE] - add to Kingdon's PE the identification of activities establing meaning through framing mechanisms. Interview participants in the process of creating policy around a coastal protection/enhancement scheme in the Netherlands. The actors begin either happy with the current scheme (don't see any problem) or are keen to implement an innovative solution (they have a solution in mind).

IPA is abductive and links interpretative policy analysis [IPA] with the MSF [MSA] (they cite two other papers that have attempted this).

Discuss they framing interaction mechanisms are used. IPE characteristics (based on other works):
- sense-making
- defining problems in others' terms
- building epistemic communities
- willing to take risks (not strictly interpretative)

This interactional framing involves actor making meaning together (rather than alone or for but not with others). ``Frame-convergent framing moves bring about reframing among other actors, thereby increasing the epistemic community''. Other framings have negative outcomes. Framing interactions (from Dewulf and Bouwen 2012):
- incorporation - include watered-down version of other frame
- accommodation - include near-exact copy of other frame
- reconnection - overcoming conflict
- disconnection - worsening conflict
- polarisation 

``convinced other actors that issues on different levels and in different sectors could be solved by using the same policy solution''

Actors had different interpretations of the problem ``the Sand Motor case represents a `frame conflict' between actors, such as the provincial government, who expect the Sand Motor to be a promising technology and actors, such as the public works agency, who feel there is no need for experimentation when lives are at stake and the technology in place works''

From interviews, constructed timelines and identified when participants perceived change in theirs or others' framings, when interactions occurred. From these determined what type of framing interactions occurred. From this they identify an individual IPE. Note a ``gradual opening up of most actors'' [Cairney's softening?]

Interesting to note that one party did not engage at the start because they did not perceive a problem - this needed other actors to reframe to solve the frame conflict. Also that polarisation was used by one group to gain power by building support - this led to a top-down order for the the other group to comply.},
  creationdate     = {2025-03-17T17:24:47},
