@article{MatukBSAHT2020,
  author           = {Fernanda Ayaviri Matuk and Jelle Hendrik Behagel and Felipe Nogueira Bello Simas and Eufran Ferreira Do Amaral and Moacir Haverroth and Esther Turnhout},
  journal          = {Ecosystems and People},
  title            = {Including diverse knowledges and worldviews in environmental assessment and planning: the Brazilian Amazon Kaxinaw\'a Nova Olinda Indigenous Land case},
  year             = {2020},
  number           = {1},
  pages            = {95--113},
  volume           = {16},
  comment          = {The Intergovernmental Science-policy Platform on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services' (IPBES) proposed the [Nature's Contribution to People] NCP framework to be inclusive of [Indigenous and Local Knowledge] ILK and [Indigenous Peoples and Local Communities] IPLC

``The NCP framework is also careful not to prioritize scientific knowledge on ecological functions and economic values over diverse knowledges, worldviews, and values, as the previous iterations of the ES framework tended to do (Martn-Lpez et al.2014). With the adoption of the concept of NCP, IPBES thus stresses the need of science-policy interfaces to advance the legitimate inclusion of diverse knowledge systems in assessments and planning, to achieve well-being, conservation, and sustainable use'' (PascualEtAl2018) p95

Challenges to the integration of ILK: p96
1. ``tendency of scientists to consider science as superior to ILK (Agrawal1995)'', leads to: 
  - resist making shared decisions with IPLC
  - extract decontextualised knowledge from ILK
2. ``disciplinary backgrounds make it difficult to establish common knowledge about the various social-ecological interplays that make  up and affect biodiversity (Carpenter et al.2009)''
3. ``ES and NCP frameworks tend to emphasize how humans depend on and benefit from nature, that is, NCP (Kenter2018; Peterson et al.2018) and focus less on PCN''

Conceptualisation in `Western' science that there are universal and value-neutral truths and that material and non-material phenomena should be addressed separately  reproduces two dichotomies: p96
- between scientific knowledge and ILK systems
- between social and natural science disciplines

critique of ecosystem services and why NCP emerged p97
but also that NCP gives limited space for the role of people shaping nature, especially the practices that fall beyond different knowledges and worldviews p99

``Post-structuralist, post-humanist, and post-colonial schools of thought ... argue that reality is multiple and that it can be understood by `pluriverses' of knowledge (Escobar2016, p. 13)'' p96

Discourses have 3 elements of meaning (Foucault): p96
- classification systems - categories that reflect items that people values and identify with
- values - qualifications that people use to signify phenomena and guide action
- aspirations - ideal images associated with needs and objectives and people and policies prioritize

This work uses the discourses of planner and indigenous actor groups to identify the resonances and incongruences between their classification systems, values, and aspirations. Data was publications, reports, legal descriptions and interviews with policy-makers and (non) governmental planners involved in an ES policy and processes implementation (SISA) 40 Kaxinaw\'as of varied ages and gender who participated in the local SISA assessment and planning p100

``In the interviews, we probed both planners and Kaxinaw\'as on their aspirations, values, and classification systems and we asked them how they perceived the participatory processes to implement SISA and how they were able to influence the inclusion of knowledge and worldviews'' using circles of dialogue (Freire 2000), participatory mapping (Albuquerque et al. 2014)  p100

[Thus this is participatory analysis of a participatory process]

``analyzed how discourses shaped assessment and planning processes by contrasting how different interview respondents and participants in the workshop reported about the extent to which they were able to influence the participatory processes and its outcomes. This enabled us to identify whether and how knowledge differences present in different discourses influenced power dynamics and affected the inclusion of diverse and relational knowledge and worldviews'' p101

Results are detailed - differences in discourses but observation that SISA discourse moves closer to that on Kaxinaw\'a in terms of non-material and material contributions that people provide to nature respectively via their knowledge, values, aspirations, and their practices. p110

In terms of the participatory processes, soil science planners retained power in deciding when Kaxinaw\'a and social scientists were involved, by judging what was relevant to them -> reduction of the diversity of knowledges and worldviews in the outcomes  p110

and more generally: ``while SISA outcomes were overall considered legitimate by Kaxinaw\'as ... a stronger voice of locals to shape processes could have resulted in a more comprehensive representation of diverse knowledges and worldviews, as well as in an enhanced legitimacy, validity, and relevance of policy outcomes'' p110

In terms of frameworks, find that PCN is still not sufficiently accounted for in NCP and ES

``Our study suggests thus that the legitimacy and effectiveness of environmental assessment and planning can be improved when actors on the science-policy interface facilitate participation  and engagement that gives voice to participants who hold different knowledge systems and disciplines, that focuses on common objectives, aspirations, and priorities which account for both people and ecosystems' roles, and that connects assessment to planning and practice'' p111},
  creationdate     = {2025-03-17T17:24:49},
  doi              = {10.1080/26395916.2020.1722752},
  keywords         = {participatory,science,thesis},
  modificationdate = {2025-03-17T17:24:49},
  owner            = {izzy_olivine},
  publisher        = {Taylor & Francis},
}

@article{PascualEtAl2018,
  author           = {Unai Pascual and Patricia Balvanera and Sandra D\'iaz and Gy\"orgy Pataki and Eva Roth and Marie Stenseke and Robert T. Watson and Esra {Ba\c{s}ak Dessane} and Mine Islar and Eszter Kelemen and Virginie Maris and Martin Quaas and Suneetha M Subramanian and Heidi Wittmer and Asia Adlan and SoEun Ahn and Yousef S. Al-Hafedh and Edward Amankwah and Stanley T. Asah and Pam Berry and Adem Bilgin and Sara J. Breslow and Craig Bullock and Daniel C\'aceres and Hamed Daly-Hassen and Eugenio Figueroa and Christopher D Golden and Erik G\'omez-Baggethun and David Gonzlez-Jimnez and Jo\"el Houdet and Hans Keune and Ritesh Kumar and Keping Ma and Peter H. May and Aroha Mead and Patrick O'Farrell and Ram Pandit and Walter Pengue and Ram\'on Pichis-Madruga and Florin Popa and Susan Preston and Diego Pacheco-Balanza and Heli Saarikoski and Bernardo B Strassburg and Marjan {van den Belt} and Madhu Verma and Fern Wickson and Noboyuki Yagi},
  journal          = {Current Opinion in Environmental Sustainability},
  title            = {Valuing nature's contributions to people: the IPBES approach},
  year             = {2018},
  issn             = {1877-3435},
  note             = {Open issue, part II},
  number           = {27},
  pages            = {7--16},
  volume           = {26},
  abstract         = {Nature is perceived and valued in starkly different and often conflicting ways. This paper presents the rationale for the inclusive valuation of nature's contributions to people (NCP) in decision making, as well as broad methodological steps for doing so. While developed within the context of the Intergovernmental Platform on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services (IPBES), this approach is more widely applicable to initiatives at the knowledge-policy interface, which require a pluralistic approach to recognizing the diversity of values. We argue that transformative practices aiming at sustainable futures would benefit from embracing such diversity, which require recognizing and addressing power relationships across stakeholder groups that hold different values on human nature-relations and NCP.},
  comment          = {Nature's Contribution to People (NCP) bridges notions of nature and a good quality of life

Recognises that there are different worldviews and values associated with NCP and present the rationale for an inclusive incorporation of the diversity of values of NCP in decision making

Emphasis in the consideration of diverse values of NCP to inform policies and everyday practices can be placed, for example on:
- food and feed
- protecting the evolutionary processes of biodiversity and the continued functioning of ecosystems
- honouring the Earth as a sacred living being or on maintaining harmonic relationships between people and nature

Contrast unidimensional value framings (e.g. economic, ecological, social, cultural) with pluralistic valuation (diverse world views). This inform the policy toolbox which is thus restricted in the single world view case.

Acknowledging diverse world views would take a social-ecological perspective, where nature, NCP and a good quality of life are seen as interdependent, and would require activating deliberative approaches towards potential conflict resolution over values. It is associated with the need to leverage power relations through participatory negotiation among stakeholders holding incommensurable values over human-nature relations. p11

Propose a 5-step approach to facilitate valuation:
1. identify the purpose
2. scope the process
3. pluralistic visualisation (methods and assessments)
4. integration and bridging - require transdisciplinarity blending expert valuation and social participatory processes
5. communication on value and review the valuation process

2 key principles:
1. valuation and value assessments require the recognition of a broad range of worldviews
2. valuation requires learning that the incorporation of values and valuation methods into decision making processes are themselves value-laden},
  creationdate     = {2025-03-17T17:24:49},
  doi              = {https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cosust.2016.12.006},
  keywords         = {values,environment,policy,thesis},
  modificationdate = {2025-03-17T17:24:49},
  owner            = {izzy_olivine},
  url              = {https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1877343517300040},
}

@article{TurnhoutMWKL2020,
  author           = {Esther Turnhout and Tamara Metze and Carina Wyborn and Nicole Klenk and Elena Louder},
  journal          = {Current Opinion in Environmental Sustainability},
  title            = {The politics of co-production: participation, power, and transformation},
  year             = {2020},
  pages            = {15--21},
  volume           = {42},
  comment          = {co-production literature has not paid sufficient attention to the role of power and politics in shaping processes and outcomes

key issue of representation: ``who participates and what values, perspectives and interests do these participants represent, and deliberation; how can all voices be voiced and included in a legitimate way''

biases towards elite actors are worrying because they result in these processes reproducing or even exacerbating existing inequalities. Elite actors (e.g. government, large NGOs, or scientists) are able to shape these processes to serve their interests because they:
- have more time and resources available
- often initiate these processes, define the scope for participation
- have more knowledge and skills
- better able to articulate a contribution that is considered relevant and important
- have strong authority that is attributed to scientific expertise vis-a-vis other knowledge systems p16
- often paid to participate as part of their professional roles, while the other participants are expected to volunteer their time
- more often invited to participate than unorganized citizens or less well-known groups

Further:
- inherent Western bias
